<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Insect Netting for Brassicas</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The best insect netting is the one that keeps pests out while still letting your brassicas grow without overheating or struggling for airflow.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, the best insect netting for brassicas is a fine-mesh, breathable cover that blocks common pests without trapping too much heat or moisture.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Brassicas like cabbage, broccoli, kale, and cauliflower are some of the most pest-targeted crops in the garden. In many cases, physical exclusion works better than reactive control.
  </p>
  <p>
    The right insect netting protects plants from common pests like cabbage moths and flea beetles while still allowing enough airflow and light for healthy growth.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Kind of Insect Netting Is Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best for most gardeners:</strong> fine-mesh insect netting that blocks small pests but remains breathable.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for heavy pest pressure:</strong> tighter mesh that prevents even small insects from reaching plants.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for warm conditions:</strong> lighter, more breathable netting that reduces heat buildup.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The most important factor is mesh size. The netting needs to be fine enough to block pests, but open enough to avoid creating a stressed growing environment.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Brassicas Benefit So Much from Insect Netting</h2>

  <p>
    Brassicas are highly attractive to a range of insects, especially early in the season. Many of these pests lay eggs directly on leaves, which quickly leads to visible damage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Insect netting works by preventing access in the first place. This is often more effective than treating problems after they appear, especially for crops that can be heavily damaged in a short time.
  </p>

  <p>
    For many gardeners, netting is one of the most reliable ways to keep brassicas clean and productive.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Mesh Size: The Most Important Decision</h2>

  <p>
    Mesh size determines what the netting can actually block.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Mesh Type</th>
          <th>Best For</th>
          <th>Tradeoff</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Fine mesh</strong></td>
          <td>Small pests like flea beetles</td>
          <td>Less airflow, slightly more heat buildup</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Medium mesh</strong></td>
          <td>Common cabbage pests</td>
          <td>Better airflow, but may allow very small insects through</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Light mesh</strong></td>
          <td>General protection and airflow</td>
          <td>Less effective against smaller pests</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    For most brassica crops, fine to medium mesh strikes the best balance between protection and growing conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Insect Netting vs Row Cover for Brassicas</h2>

  <p>
    Both insect netting and row cover can protect brassicas, but they are not exactly the same tool.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Insect netting:</strong> focuses on pest exclusion with better airflow.</li>
    <li><strong>Row cover:</strong> provides more temperature buffering but may trap more heat.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In early spring, row cover can help with both cold and pests. As temperatures rise, insect netting often becomes the better choice because it allows more airflow while still blocking pests.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    For the full comparison, see <a href="/guides/insect-netting-vs-row-cover-for-brassicas/">insect netting vs row cover for brassicas</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in Insect Netting</h2>

  <h3>1. Mesh Size That Matches Your Pest Pressure</h3>
  <p>
    Choose mesh based on the pests you are trying to block. Finer mesh offers more protection but may reduce airflow slightly.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Breathability</h3>
  <p>
    Good airflow helps prevent overheating and keeps plants growing steadily under cover.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Durability</h3>
  <p>
    Netting is often reused across seasons, so it should be strong enough to handle repeated setup and removal.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Ease of Installation</h3>
  <p>
    Netting should be easy to secure over beds and simple to lift when checking or harvesting.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Size That Matches Your Beds</h3>
  <p>
    Netting that fits your garden layout cleanly is easier to use and less likely to leave gaps where pests can enter.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Hoops Usually Make Netting Work Better</h2>

  <p>
    While netting can sometimes rest directly on plants, using hoops usually improves performance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hoops create space between the netting and the plants, improve airflow, and make it easier to manage the cover without disturbing the crop.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is especially helpful for crops like broccoli and cabbage that grow upward and outward over time.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-clips-and-hoops-for-securing-frost-cloth/">best clips and hoops for securing frost cloth</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Insect Netting Is Worth It</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>You regularly deal with cabbage worms or moths.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Flea beetles are damaging young plants.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>You want to avoid repeated pest treatments.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>You prefer prevention over reaction.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In these situations, netting is often one of the most effective tools you can use.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    The effectiveness of insect netting depends heavily on how well it is sealed around the edges.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even small gaps can allow pests to enter, especially early in the season when plants are small and the cover is not yet fully secured.
  </p>

  <p>
    In many cases, proper installation matters as much as the netting itself.
  </p>
</section>

