<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Insect Netting</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Choosing mesh that is too open:</strong> allows key pests through.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring heat buildup:</strong> especially later in spring.</li>
    <li><strong>Not securing edges properly:</strong> reduces effectiveness dramatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Using netting too late:</strong> after pests have already laid eggs.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best results usually come from using netting early and setting it up carefully.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most brassica crops, buy fine to medium mesh insect netting that is breathable, durable, and easy to secure over your beds. Pair it with simple hoops if possible to improve airflow and ease of use.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose finer mesh if pest pressure is high, and lean toward lighter, more breathable netting if conditions are warm and airflow matters more. In most cases, prevention with netting is easier than dealing with pests after they arrive.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best insect netting is the one that keeps pests out while still letting your plants grow comfortably underneath it.
  </p>
